INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('880', '1', '2013-07-29 07:28:32', '2013-07-29 07:28:32', '<div>\r\n\r\nIt is important for Maryland doctors to carefully review their patients medical records and to communicate potential risks with their colleagues. Failure to do so could result in grave medical errors that lead to serious brain injury.\r\n\r\nSoon after a girl was born, she had a heart transplant that enabled her to lead a healthy, normal life. However, when the girl was 4 years old, she developed a cold. When the girls mother called the hospital for instructions, the doctor allegedly recommended that she give Afrin to the child, despite warnings from the childs cardiologist.\r\n\r\nFor an unknown reason, the doctor had dismissed the cardiologists orders. When the girls mother gave Afrin to the girl, it apparently put additional strain on her heart, and she stopped breathing. Ultimately, it caused severe brain damage, and the girl, who is now 8 years old, has not been the same since, and it is likely that her condition is permanent. According to the girls mother, she now requires constant care. Even though the hospital alleges that Afrin did not cause the girls brain damage, the judge ruled in favor of the girls family. The hospital, which continues to treat the girl, awarded $15.2 million to the family.\r\n\r\nEspecially when the victim is a child, brain injuries are devastating for the victims family members. Fortunately, the accident compensation that the victims family received will enable them to cover the childs medical expenses. People in similar situations may want to talk to a personal injury attorney about their case.\r\n\r\n<b>Source:</b><strong>Source: </strong>KIRO TV, <a href=\"http://www.kirotv.com/news/news/judge-awards-152-million-girl-brain-damage-after-h/nYpDp/\" target=\"_blank\">Judge awards $15.2 million for girl with brain damage after hospital error</a>, Amy Clancy, July 12, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Hospital pays $15.2 million to brain injury victim', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'hospital-pays-15-2-million-to-brain-injury-victim', '', '', '2014-02-28 07:29:32', '2014-02-28 07:29:32', '', '0', 'http://odelugojohnsonllc.com/?p=880', '0', 'post', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('881', '1', '2014-02-28 07:29:32', '2014-02-28 07:29:32', '<div>\r\n\r\nIt is important for Maryland doctors to carefully review their patients medical records and to communicate potential risks with their colleagues. Failure to do so could result in grave medical errors that lead to serious brain injury.\r\n\r\nSoon after a girl was born, she had a heart transplant that enabled her to lead a healthy, normal life. However, when the girl was 4 years old, she developed a cold. When the girls mother called the hospital for instructions, the doctor allegedly recommended that she give Afrin to the child, despite warnings from the childs cardiologist.\r\n\r\nFor an unknown reason, the doctor had dismissed the cardiologists orders. When the girls mother gave Afrin to the girl, it apparently put additional strain on her heart, and she stopped breathing. Ultimately, it caused severe brain damage, and the girl, who is now 8 years old, has not been the same since, and it is likely that her condition is permanent. According to the girls mother, she now requires constant care. Even though the hospital alleges that Afrin did not cause the girls brain damage, the judge ruled in favor of the girls family. The hospital, which continues to treat the girl, awarded $15.2 million to the family.\r\n\r\nEspecially when the victim is a child, brain injuries are devastating for the victims family members. Fortunately, the accident compensation that the victims family received will enable them to cover the childs medical expenses. People in similar situations may want to talk to a personal injury attorney about their case.\r\n\r\n<b>Source:</b><strong>Source: </strong>KIRO TV, <a href=\"http://www.kirotv.com/news/news/judge-awards-152-million-girl-brain-damage-after-h/nYpDp/\" target=\"_blank\">Judge awards $15.2 million for girl with brain damage after hospital error</a>, Amy Clancy, July 12, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Hospital pays $15.2 million to brain injury victim', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '880-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-28 07:29:32', '2014-02-28 07:29:32', '', '880', 'http://odelugojohnsonllc.com/880-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('882', '1', '2013-06-28 07:29:55', '2013-06-28 07:29:55', '<div>\r\n\r\nMedical breakthroughs are always promising, especially with traumatic injuries that in the past would be fatal or cause permanent disability. But what types of medical testing are ethical and acceptable for doctors to perform on patients? Is it ever okay to try out a new procedure or drug on a patient with a traumatic injury, without the patients or familys consent?\r\n\r\nDoctors in several areas across the country are planning to take part in a large research effort to treat patients with serious brain trauma. The study is to test if the female hormone progesterone is effective in helping to heal the human brain after a brain injury. Researchers plan to take advantage of a federal law that exempts permission to perform a study, since timing is crucial in the minutes after a serious head injury to prevent further brain damage.\r\n\r\nDoctors say it usually takes about four and a half hours to obtain consent from a victims family for enrollment in a study, while damage from brain trauma can begin immediately after the injury. But ethicists say that its never okay to perform research without the permission of a victim or the family, and that just being in an accident doesnt automatically grant doctors license to start a study or unfounded treatment.\r\n\r\nDoctors know that there can be legal liability for enrolling a patient in a study without consent. Medical professionals in Maryland can be held responsible for mistakes even if permission is granted. This makes the decision to begin a study without obtaining permission a risky one. In the end, it may come down to people deciding, before an accident occurs, whether or not they would want to become part of a trial if they were unable to grant permission at the time.\r\n\r\n<b>Source:</b>The Boston Globe, <a href=\"http://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/health-wellness/2013/06/07/researchers-look-conduct-research-without-consent-brain-injury-study/UsEejnzwAUvpKq2eI8TJRL/story.html\" target=\"_blank\">Hospitals want to test drug with no consent</a>, Chelsea Conaboy, June 8, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Researchers debating testing brain injury victims without consent', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'researchers-debating-testing-brain-injury-victims-without-consent', '', '', '2014-02-28 07:30:57', '2014-02-28 07:30:57', '', '0', 'http://odelugojohnsonllc.com/?p=882', '0', 'post', '', '0');
