INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('888', '1', '2013-01-23 07:33:56', '2013-01-23 07:33:56', '<div>\r\n\r\nWhen someone suffers a debilitating injury requiring long-term medical care which could have been prevented, often another party is held liable for the victim\'s compensation. The most cut-and-dry cases usually involve litigation against the person or party directly involved in the victim\'s injuries -- such as the perpetrator of a crime or one who causes an accident. Other times, a business or government agency can be held accountable if the evidence points that the situation was caused by negligence and could have been avoided.\r\n\r\nRecently, the city of Chicago settled with the family of a young woman who received a spinal injury that paralyzed her from the waist down and brain damage that resulted in a permanent comatose state. The woman was detained by police after having a manic episode during a plane trip from California. Despite her parents\' requests to the police not to release their daughter and instead take her to a psychiatric hospital for evaluation because she suffered from bipolar disorder, the woman was released in an area known to have high crime.\r\n\r\nAfter her release, the young woman was abducted, gang-raped and then fell from a 7-story window, suffering life-changing injuries. During a deposition, police authorities admitted they should have retained her for psychiatric evaluation instead of releasing her. With her catastrophic injuries, the family\'s medical expenses will continue throughout the rest of the woman\'s life.\r\n\r\nThe settlement of this lawsuit illustrates how city officials have a responsibility to ensure the safety of those under their care who are mentally or physically vulnerable. Maryland residents may be eligible for compensation when another party is proven responsible for permanent injuries to themselves or family members.\r\n\r\n<strong>Source: </strong>Chicago Tribune, \"<a href=\"http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-01-15/news/ct-met-chicago-police-abuse-settlements-0115-20130115_1_eilman-case-police-misconduct-christina-eilman\" target=\"_blank\">Chicago to pay $33 million to settle 2 cases of police misconduct</a>,\" David Heinzmann, Jan. 15, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'City settlement of $22.5 million for woman\'s permanent disability', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'city-settlement-of-22-5-million-for-womans-permanent-disability', '', '', '2014-02-28 07:35:09', '2014-02-28 07:35:09', '', '0', 'http://odelugojohnsonllc.com/?p=888', '0', 'post', '', '0');
