INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('928', '1', '2013-12-28 09:42:46', '2013-12-28 09:42:46', '<div>\r\n\r\nThe truth of the matter is that thousands of babies are born with life-threatening conditions every year in Maryland, and many continue to face difficulties their entire lives. And while countless families approach such obstacles with grace and compassion, sometimes they are left to live with the consequences of others avoidable mistakes. A jury recently ruled in favor of a family that filed a medical malpractice lawsuit against several medical staff for causing their son to endure potentially fatal birth injuries.\r\n\r\nThe child at the heart of the case is now nine years old. At the time of his premature birth, the child experienced a life-threatening medical condition associated with his early arrival. The boys parents claim that the nurse practitioner and two doctors attending to their son did not respond to his medical crisis in the correct manner, which ultimately resulted in his current medical state. After having a section of his intestines removed, the young boy must rely on a feeding tube for nutrition.\r\n\r\nFor its part, the hospital where the child was born claims that the boys condition is unfortunate. However, the hospital contends that his care and medical needs were handled correctly throughout the entire incident. In its argument, the hospital added that the boys medical condition takes the lives of many children every year.\r\n\r\nThe family of the boy apparently agreed to a maximum and minimum award figure with the defendants in the lawsuit before any verdict was issued. As a result, they may receive the maximum judgment of $5.3 million even though the jury awarded them $30 million. They may now pursue other means of achieving the full amount.\r\n\r\n<b>Source:</b>boston.com, <a href=\"http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/2013/11/21/lowell-family-receive-least-malpractice-suit-against-tufts-medical-center/LE6KSbzmwkLnJAgrTeqrVI/story.html\" target=\"_blank\">Lowell family to receive at least $5m in malpractice suit against Tufts Medical Center</a>, Travis Anderson, Nov. 21, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Nine years later, family wins birth injury lawsuit', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'nine-years-later-family-wins-birth-injury-lawsuit', '', '', '2014-02-28 09:43:39', '2014-02-28 09:43:39', '', '0', 'http://odelugojohnsonllc.com/?p=928', '0', 'post', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('929', '1', '2014-02-28 09:43:39', '2014-02-28 09:43:39', '<div>\r\n\r\nThe truth of the matter is that thousands of babies are born with life-threatening conditions every year in Maryland, and many continue to face difficulties their entire lives. And while countless families approach such obstacles with grace and compassion, sometimes they are left to live with the consequences of others avoidable mistakes. A jury recently ruled in favor of a family that filed a medical malpractice lawsuit against several medical staff for causing their son to endure potentially fatal birth injuries.\r\n\r\nThe child at the heart of the case is now nine years old. At the time of his premature birth, the child experienced a life-threatening medical condition associated with his early arrival. The boys parents claim that the nurse practitioner and two doctors attending to their son did not respond to his medical crisis in the correct manner, which ultimately resulted in his current medical state. After having a section of his intestines removed, the young boy must rely on a feeding tube for nutrition.\r\n\r\nFor its part, the hospital where the child was born claims that the boys condition is unfortunate. However, the hospital contends that his care and medical needs were handled correctly throughout the entire incident. In its argument, the hospital added that the boys medical condition takes the lives of many children every year.\r\n\r\nThe family of the boy apparently agreed to a maximum and minimum award figure with the defendants in the lawsuit before any verdict was issued. As a result, they may receive the maximum judgment of $5.3 million even though the jury awarded them $30 million. They may now pursue other means of achieving the full amount.\r\n\r\n<b>Source:</b>boston.com, <a href=\"http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/2013/11/21/lowell-family-receive-least-malpractice-suit-against-tufts-medical-center/LE6KSbzmwkLnJAgrTeqrVI/story.html\" target=\"_blank\">Lowell family to receive at least $5m in malpractice suit against Tufts Medical Center</a>, Travis Anderson, Nov. 21, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Nine years later, family wins birth injury lawsuit', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '928-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-28 09:43:39', '2014-02-28 09:43:39', '', '928', 'http://odelugojohnsonllc.com/928-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('930', '1', '2013-11-24 09:44:31', '2013-11-24 09:44:31', '<div>\r\n\r\nIn many instances, proving that a medical physician is liable for negligence or misdiagnosis is only half the battle. Introducing a medical malpractice lawsuit can be a long and difficult process--one that doesnt simply end at determining fault. The jury charged with ruling on a malpractice trial is often also responsible for deciding what the appropriate amount of damages owed to the victim/s is in the case. Failing to come to an agreement on damages can compromise the entire case in some instances. For example, a mistrial was recently called in a case where a Maryland jury was unable to agree on the damages to award to the victim.\r\n\r\nThe specific case in question is only one of hundreds filed against a prominent Maryland cardiologist. The trial, which was the first of its kind to result in a guilty verdict against the doctor, was also the first where the defendant himself testified. The other cases ended in settlements.\r\n\r\nWhile the cardiologist identified as the defendant in the medical malpractice lawsuit claims that he did his job, the plaintiff in the case accuses him of misdiagnosis and performing unnecessary stent surgery that resulted in the plaintiff sustaining emotional and medical complications, in addition to financial difficulties. Alleging that he was forced to end his career as a result of the surgery, the plaintiff requested $50 million in damages.\r\n\r\nThe mistrial was declared after jurors spent almost a week trying to determine how much the victim should receive in damages. The judge ruled that the jury could only find the hospital liable for damages, even though the doctor was found guilty of malpractice. Because of the mistrial, some experts believe another trial may be necessary to determine damages.\r\n\r\n<b>Source:</b>Baltimore Sun, <a href=\"http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2013-11-06/health/bs-md-midei-trial-20131106_1_glenn-weinberg-mark-midei-jury-deadlocks\" target=\"_blank\">Mistrial in Midei stent case as jury deadlocks on damages</a>, Jessica Anderson Nov. 6, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Inability to determine damages stalls medical malpractice suit', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'inability-to-determine-damages-stalls-medical-malpractice-suit', '', '', '2014-02-28 09:46:12', '2014-02-28 09:46:12', '', '0', 'http://odelugojohnsonllc.com/?p=930', '0', 'post', '', '0');
