INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('982', '1', '2013-01-05 10:37:21', '2013-01-05 10:37:21', '<div>\r\n\r\nFor many people who are being treated in a hospital, a key aspect of their care is the record that follows them around. Most people would like to assume that their medical records are accurate and reliable. However, in the transition from paper medical records to digital ones, there is the possibility for hospital error and the failure to diagnose a serious condition.\r\n\r\nThe federal government knows this. In fact, recently the Department of Health and Human Services recently urged the software companies that create the records to cooperate more with hospitals and other institutions to reduce errors and make the records safer. But they stopped short of requiring this, leaving open the possibility that gaps in the system still exist.\r\n\r\nIn fact, observers say that what has been done is not nearly enough, calling them \"baby steps\" on the way to meaningful reform. Part of the issue is that the use of computerized records systems -- technically known as EHRs, electronic health records -- has exploded in recent months. This is because Medicare has been offering payment incentives for doctors and hospitals to create EHRs, which theoretically should improve the quality and consistency of patient care.\r\n\r\nHowever, unexpected consequences have come from the preponderance of EHRs. One issue is that sometimes the font on the screen is too small for caregivers to read; this has led them to click on the wrong medication, which could be dangerous or fatal for a patient. Another problem is misdated, lost or out-of-date test results showing up in the records, which could cause unnecessary procedures to be ordered -- or urgently needed treatment to be delayed.\r\n\r\n<strong>Source: </strong>Kaiser Health News, \"<a href=\"http://capsules.kaiserhealthnews.org/index.php/2012/12/hhs-stops-short-of-calling-for-safety-regulation-of-digital-records/\" target=\"_blank\">HHS Stops Short Of Calling For Safety Regulation Of Digital Records</a>,\" Jay Hancock, Dec. 21, 2012\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Electronic health records system causing plenty of problems', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'electronic-health-records-system-causing-plenty-of-problems', '', '', '2014-02-28 10:38:20', '2014-02-28 10:38:20', '', '0', 'http://odelugojohnsonllc.com/?p=982', '0', 'post', '', '0');
